WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.000
Um, uh, so just to remind everyone, you know, when we talk about AML and we talk about outcomes,

00:00:07.000 --> 00:00:10.240
we actually have two different, uh, classification systems now, right?

00:00:10.260 --> 00:00:15.000
We have ELN 2022, which is how patients respond to intensive chemotherapy, but depending on

00:00:15.000 --> 00:00:18.500
the treatments that we use, of course, you know, different mutations may predict for

00:00:18.500 --> 00:00:21.840
different, um, outcomes based on the therapy being used.

00:00:21.880 --> 00:00:26.440
And so the ELN 2024 is the first to try to, you know, talk about how patients will do

00:00:26.440 --> 00:00:28.060
to lower intensive therapies.

00:00:28.060 --> 00:00:34.960
And you'll notice IDH2 and IDH1 are now considered favorable risk, um, particularly IDH2 when

00:00:34.960 --> 00:00:40.580
used with, with HMA venetoclax is, is quite favorable and IDH1, the asterisk is there

00:00:40.580 --> 00:00:44.560
highlighting the fact that really, regardless of what other mutations are co-mutated with

00:00:44.560 --> 00:00:48.600
the IDH1, they do quite well with AZA-IVO, the IDH1 inhibitor.

00:00:48.740 --> 00:00:54.180
So just kind of as, as background, um, and then just to remind everyone also that, you

00:00:54.180 --> 00:00:56.820
know, we talk about IDH mutations, but they're really not all the same.

00:00:56.820 --> 00:00:57.820
Um, IDH2.

00:00:58.060 --> 00:01:01.540
IDH2 is much more often kind of an early clonal mutation.

00:01:01.540 --> 00:01:03.960
You can see that in the kind of the brown figure in the center.

00:01:04.440 --> 00:01:09.720
Um, IDH1 is often, um, um, kind of happens a little bit later, although still is, uh,

00:01:09.720 --> 00:01:13.020
earlier than the signaling mutations like RAS and FLT3 that come later.

00:01:13.500 --> 00:01:16.720
Um, and then when it, it's a, it's a busy heat map, but it's just trying to highlight

00:01:16.720 --> 00:01:20.680
the fact that the different mutations often have different co-occurring mutations.

00:01:20.680 --> 00:01:27.620
So IDH2, R140 in particular has often NPM1 and FLT3 FLT3 co, uh, co-mutated alongside,

00:01:27.820 --> 00:01:28.040
whereas IDH2 is much more common.

00:01:28.040 --> 00:01:30.420
So IDH2, R172 is very different, right?

00:01:30.480 --> 00:01:32.340
You see type 2, B-core, DNMT3A.

00:01:32.720 --> 00:01:37.860
Very rarely will you have a FLT3 or an NPM1 and IDH1 somewhere in the middle, uh, more

00:01:37.860 --> 00:01:42.080
often with adverse risks, cyto and P53, unfortunately, compared to IDH2.

00:01:43.600 --> 00:01:45.440
And then, you know, how do we treat these patients?

00:01:45.520 --> 00:01:46.380
So this is an analysis.

00:01:46.520 --> 00:01:50.980
This is kind of more of an MD Anderson specific where we give venetoclax with intensive chemotherapy.

00:01:51.300 --> 00:01:55.120
And just to highlight that, you know, these are younger patients that are getting intensive

00:01:55.120 --> 00:01:55.680
chemotherapy.

00:01:55.680 --> 00:01:58.020
We add venetoclax, IDH2 mutation.

00:01:58.020 --> 00:02:00.300
The IDH2 mutated patients are that light blue curve along the top.

00:02:00.440 --> 00:02:01.580
They do particularly well.

00:02:02.020 --> 00:02:05.960
For some reason, the IDH1 mutated patients tend not to do as well.

00:02:06.060 --> 00:02:11.920
This is a small analysis, but, you know, they're some of the least, um, likely to stay in a

00:02:11.920 --> 00:02:13.680
remission with intensive chemo.

00:02:13.680 --> 00:02:17.320
Then just highlighting the fact that we say IDH mutations are so ven sensitive, but it

00:02:17.320 --> 00:02:21.160
really, I think is overrepresented by the IDH2 mutated patients.

00:02:22.460 --> 00:02:27.320
Um, and this just highlights further that if you have an IDH1 mutation, you got intensive

00:02:27.320 --> 00:02:27.920
chemo then.

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:33.040
You're going to do especially well if you transition to a transplant, whereas the IDH2

00:02:33.040 --> 00:02:35.580
mutated patients really seem to be more like NPM1.

00:02:35.680 --> 00:02:39.820
You may be cured with intensive chemo alone without the need to proceed to transplant.

00:02:41.560 --> 00:02:44.680
Um, what else can you do for younger patients getting intensive chemo?

00:02:44.760 --> 00:02:46.780
Certainly you can add the IDH inhibitors, right?

00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:47.960
Ivocidinib, N-acidinib.

00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:53.600
This is a study that was reported and published over five years ago now, um, where, you know,

00:02:53.600 --> 00:02:57.860
when you look at the IDH1, they're not, they look to be doing particularly well.

00:02:57.980 --> 00:03:00.580
Especially when you consider a third or secondary AML.

00:03:00.680 --> 00:03:03.260
The median age here is in the mid third, mid sixties.

00:03:03.600 --> 00:03:09.180
So maybe again, highlighting the fact that adding an IDH1 in particular may be of benefit.

00:03:09.500 --> 00:03:12.280
IDH2s do well in general, but not quite as well.

00:03:12.360 --> 00:03:17.180
And then there was a follow-up at ASH that Eitan presented with long-term follow-up.

00:03:17.240 --> 00:03:19.960
Again, highlighting this kind of relatively flat curve.

00:03:20.080 --> 00:03:22.420
Patients seem to be doing well staying in remission.

00:03:23.200 --> 00:03:27.280
Um, and, um, and half of those patients did undergo stem cell transplant.

00:03:27.960 --> 00:03:29.820
Um, which I think is also important to remember.

00:03:31.260 --> 00:03:40.980
So just to kind of serve as the background to the Hovon AMLSG study, which has been enrolling, um, and completed enrollment in 2023 and 2024.

00:03:40.980 --> 00:03:42.460
And I, I don't know for sure.

00:03:42.460 --> 00:03:50.700
I'm not involved in this, but I, I think, um, this may be coming to a, uh, summer meeting near us where we may hear some of these initial results.

00:03:53.040 --> 00:03:55.880
Um, but to talk then about triplets, right?

00:03:55.880 --> 00:03:57.940
We're talking all the more about triplet.

00:03:57.940 --> 00:04:05.800
We're talking about regimens these days using an HMA, using venetoclax and adding a targeted therapy, um, adding the IDH inhibitors were some of the earliest triplets.

00:04:05.800 --> 00:04:16.440
And we now have recently reported on the first 60 newly diagnosed patients getting a triplet with either aza, ven, ivo, or oral decitabine, venetoclax, and ivo, or ena.

00:04:16.860 --> 00:04:23.260
Um, it's a busy slide, but just to highlight the fact that we're really not seeing early mortality.

00:04:23.260 --> 00:04:24.860
We're not seeing early toxicity.

00:04:24.860 --> 00:04:27.820
IDH inhibitors are pretty easy to add to HMA venue.

00:04:27.920 --> 00:04:29.720
We don't have a lot of Cytopenias.

00:04:29.720 --> 00:04:34.700
You'll notice about 22% of the population has a co-occurring NPM1 mutation.

00:04:34.700 --> 00:04:39.920
You are flip three because we tend to prioritize flip three triplets if they have flip three mutations.

00:04:39.920 --> 00:04:44.640
Um, and 7% had a P53 mutation.

00:04:44.640 --> 00:04:46.040
Almost everyone responded.

00:04:46.040 --> 00:04:52.440
The first bar graph shows overall response rate over 90% for both IDH1 and IDH2.

00:04:52.440 --> 00:04:57.900
Um, the treated secondary AML patients were allowed on the oral decitabine study.

00:04:57.900 --> 00:05:13.700
Many of the AML patients have had a prior HMA, many have had prior venetoclax, and so when you take those patients and analyze them separately, you look at the non-treated secondary AML patients, the response rate is 100%, um, with pretty impressive, you know, two-year overall survival.

00:05:13.700 --> 00:05:17.100
This is still a relatively early study, and we're following these patients up.

00:05:17.100 --> 00:05:27.880
Um, but, you know, one of the questions that Vinay was asking me is, like, let's talk about the co-occurring mutations along with the IDH mutations.

00:05:27.880 --> 00:05:28.300
So, let's talk about the co-occurring mutations along with the IDH mutations.

00:05:28.300 --> 00:05:31.060
So, that's the first column, right?

00:05:31.120 --> 00:05:39.360
You can see survival, event-free survival, duration of remission, and NPM1 mutated patients do well, but the ones that aren't NPM1 mutated patients do well also.

00:05:40.220 --> 00:05:44.140
KRAS and NRAS in these triplet regimens isn't statistically significant.

00:05:44.140 --> 00:05:47.000
With more patients and more follow-up, probably will be.

00:05:47.140 --> 00:05:52.140
You know, you do start to see a splaying of EFS, and certainly P53, right?

00:05:52.180 --> 00:05:55.060
Those few patients with P53, they respond, but then they relapse.

00:05:55.060 --> 00:05:57.860
So, this, unfortunately, is not going to be the cure-all for that.

00:05:57.860 --> 00:06:11.800
Um, what's interesting about the mutations that relapse, and this is kind of a busy slide, but what yellow are emerging mutations, and purple is if they, it was there at the beginning, and then you lost it.

00:06:11.920 --> 00:06:19.680
So, of the six IDH1 mutated patients that have relapsed on this study to date, only one had a detectable IDH1 when they relapsed.

00:06:19.680 --> 00:06:23.080
For the IDH2, four relapsed, two of them persisted, two didn't.

00:06:23.160 --> 00:06:27.720
So, you're actually starting to see this looks to be very effective at eradicating.

00:06:27.840 --> 00:06:29.000
That IDH1 clone.

00:06:29.460 --> 00:06:32.740
Um, and relapses tend to be IDH wild type.

00:06:32.860 --> 00:06:38.420
Um, but what they do relapse with tends to be a little bit, uh, you know, there's not a clear pattern.

00:06:38.420 --> 00:06:42.260
You see some, some differentiating mutations like SWAMP1 and CBP-alpha.

00:06:42.380 --> 00:06:43.920
You do see some signaling mutations.

00:06:44.460 --> 00:06:45.840
Um, but you don't see that switch, right?

00:06:45.880 --> 00:06:47.920
The IDH1 to the IDH2 or vice versa.

00:06:48.180 --> 00:06:53.620
And we're not seeing kind of those site mutations kind of at the enzymatic, uh, binding site.

00:06:53.720 --> 00:06:57.720
So, just to remember, when you're using monotherapy, the IDH inhibitors, you,

00:06:57.820 --> 00:07:01.380
you tend to have those second site mutations kind of preventing drug from binding.

00:07:01.620 --> 00:07:04.980
You could have that isoform switching IDH1 flips to IDH2.

00:07:05.120 --> 00:07:07.380
We're not seeing either of those when we're doing triplets.

00:07:07.380 --> 00:07:12.180
We tend to see that the non-2HG related, either the kind of transcription mutations,

00:07:12.360 --> 00:07:15.680
reinstituting the, the block and differentiation or these signal mutations.

00:07:17.280 --> 00:07:22.780
Um, there is now a, uh, European study of AZA-IVO as the background,

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:27.800
plus minus venetoclax to see if indeed adding a triplet to IDH1 mutated patients

00:07:27.980 --> 00:07:33.580
will be as what we hope as effective and tolerable as what we've seen thus far at our institution.

00:07:34.340 --> 00:07:39.480
Um, and just one really quick, um, it's, it's, you know, a whole talk in and of itself,

00:07:39.480 --> 00:07:44.980
but Paresh Vyas, um, in Oxford looked at all of our kind of resistant and relapsing and

00:07:44.980 --> 00:07:52.020
responding samples and was able to identify by doing single-cell and RNA-seq on, um, on

00:07:52.020 --> 00:07:57.540
samples on our triplet trial that you can actually predict who's going to relapse or not within the

00:07:57.540 --> 00:08:04.560
first three cycles. So if you have kind of this small residual, um, immunophenotypic leukemic

00:08:04.560 --> 00:08:09.800
population in the LSC fraction, those patients were destined to relapse. It often happens six

00:08:09.800 --> 00:08:13.440
to 12 months later, but it would happen. Whereas if you didn't see that, those patients were,

00:08:13.900 --> 00:08:18.540
seemed to be effectively cured. So you probably are going to be able to identify who is prone or

00:08:18.540 --> 00:08:23.900
destined to relapse or not once we get some of these more fancy analytics able to be done in

00:08:23.900 --> 00:08:27.480
real time. And so with that, I will close. You don't need to,

00:08:27.480 --> 00:08:29.520
read my conclusions, and I will.
